Overall trend lines

```r
library(tidyverse)
library(DBI)
db <- dbConnect(odbc::odbc(), \ResearchDB\)
wc <- tbl(db, \apb_wordcounts\) %>% collect()

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


We can start by evaluating how many newspaper pages/words we have for each of the two corpora. These plots come from a materialized view in the database.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->

```r
ggplot(wc, aes(x = year, y = wordcount, color = corpus)) +
  geom_line() + geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1800, 1950, 20)) +
  scale_y_log10(label = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Word count for ChronAm and NCNP")

ggplot(wc, aes(x = year, y = pages, color = corpus)) +
  geom_line() + geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1800, 1950, 20)) +
  scale_y_log10(label = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Page count for ChronAm and NCNP")

```r
wc %>% 
  select(-wordcount) %>% 
  mutate(pages = as.integer(pages)) %>% 
  spread(corpus, pages)

```

Both plots show the same chronological boundaries to the corpus. There is no significant coverage in Chronicling America until 1836 at the earliest, with a serious dropoff after 1922. NCNP as whole cuts off in 1899. It doesnt have serious coverage until the 1820s, with either 1816 or 1828 being a good starting date. These dates can be settled on later, but this shows that if we get some wonkiness in the trends lines, this would be a good place to cut off.
